    "costs": null,
    "actions_taken": [
      "Determine if there should be restricted areas on the rig during adverse weather conditions",
      "Communicate restricted locations to all personnel during pre-tour and relevant meetings",
      "Assess helideck capabilities and challenges for landing under adverse weather",
      "Suspend non-critical work if conditions are unfavorable",
      "Suspend operations if winch-down is only viable medivac option",
      "Place additional restricted access signs around the rig based on weather-related restrictions",
      "Conduct safety meeting for each tour focused on adverse weather awareness"
    ],
    "summary": "On 10-NOV-2024 at 0145 hours, an injured person (IP) on the Transocean Deepwater Invictus drillship was struck by a 15-foot wave while standing at the aft handrail despite being informed the stern was secured due to deteriorating weather and building seas. The IP was knocked approximately 20 feet across the rig, possibly striking a bollard, and sustained a fractured right femur. The IP had less than one year offshore experience and was not assigned duties in the secured area but chose to enter it to observe the water.",
    "recommendations": [
      "BSEE Houma District recommends the Office of Incident Investigations issue a safety alert/bulletin regarding this incident"
    ],
